## Two MySQL databases (read this first)

A satellite uses **two** databases on your MySQL server ‚Äî **not** ‚Äújust the main Seismo database‚Äù.

| Which | Config constant / file | Purpose |
|-------|-------------------------|---------|
| **Mothership** | `SEISMO_MOTHERSHIP_DB` in `config.local.php` (from JSON: `{{MOTHERSHIP_DB}}`) | **Entry data** ‚Äî feeds, emails, Lex, Leg, ‚Ä¶ Seismo **reads** only (`SELECT`). Ingestion runs on the mothership. |
| **Satellite (local)** | `DB_NAME` / `DB_USER` / `DB_PASS` in `config.local.php` | **Scores & local state** ‚Äî `entry_scores`, `system_config`, labels, favourites. PHP connects here first; Magnitu **pushes** scores into this DB. |

You must **`CREATE DATABASE`** for the satellite side (¬ß2), **`GRANT ALL`** on that **`DB_NAME`**, and **`GRANT SELECT`** on **`{{MOTHERSHIP_DB}}`** for the same MySQL user. If you skip the satellite database or only grant the mothership, you will get connection errors (e.g. `1044 Access denied`).

## 1. Upload

Upload the entire contents of this folder to your webspace at the target URL. The satellite expects a subdirectory layout:

    {{MOTHERSHIP_URL_BASE}}/seismo-{{SLUG}}/

## 2. Create the satellite's own MySQL database

The **exact** `DB_NAME` / `DB_USER` / `DB_PASS` in `config.local.php` must match what you create here. Prefer **underscores** in names (not hyphens) ‚Äî some shared hosts reject hyphenated database names.

    CREATE DATABASE `{{DB_NAME}}` CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci;
    CREATE USER '{{DB_USER}}'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY '<DB_PASS from config.local.php>';

    -- Satellite needs write access to its own scoring tables:
    GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON `{{DB_NAME}}`.* TO '{{DB_USER}}'@'%';

    -- Satellite needs read access to the mothership's entries:
    GRANT SELECT ON `{{MOTHERSHIP_DB}}`.* TO '{{DB_USER}}'@'%';

    FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

On many hosts, PHP connects as `'user'@'localhost'` ‚Äî if `1044` persists, repeat `GRANT` for `'{{DB_USER}}'@'localhost'` as well (or create the user with `@'localhost'` instead of `'%'` to match your provider‚Äôs panel).

## 3. Import the scoring schema

    mysql -h {{DB_HOST}} -u {{DB_USER}} -p {{DB_NAME}} < sql/install.sql

This creates `entry_scores`, `magnitu_labels`, `system_config`, `entry_favourites` and seeds the satellite's Magnitu API key + profile slug (`system_config` is the 0.5 key/value store; it replaces the old `magnitu_config` name).

## 4. First visit / migrations

Browse to `{{MOTHERSHIP_URL_BASE}}/seismo-{{SLUG}}/`. Run `?action=migrate&key=‚Ä¶` once if your Seismo 0.5 install expects it (see mothership `SEISMO_MIGRATE_KEY` in `config.local.php`). That applies any remaining schema (e.g. `plugin_run_log`) beyond this bootstrap SQL.

If `?action=migrate` creates an **empty** legacy table named `magnitu_config` (base schema dump) while `system_config` already exists from `install.sql`, migration 005 skips the rename. You may `DROP TABLE magnitu_config` when it is empty‚Äîonly `system_config` is used at runtime.

The timeline stays empty until Magnitu pushes scores for this profile.

## 5. Point Magnitu at this satellite

In Magnitu, on the `{{MAGNITU_PROFILE}}` profile's settings, paste:

    Push target URL: {{MOTHERSHIP_URL_BASE}}/seismo-{{SLUG}}/
    API key:         {{API_KEY}}

Then push scores + recipe. The satellite's timeline will now show the investigation-lead + important entries for this profile.

